What is R?

The R Project for Statistical Computing state the following:

  • R is a language and environment for statistical computing and graphics.
  • It is a GNU project which is similar to the S language.
  • S and R are often the language of choice for research in statistical methodology.
  • R is designed around a true computer language, and it allows users to add additional functionality by defining new functions.
  • R is a computing environment within which statistical techniques are implemented.

What is R?

The folks at Inside-R give the following definition:

“…R is a complete, interactive, object-oriented language: designed by statisticians, for statisticians. The language provides objects, operators and functions that make the process of exploring, modeling, and visualizing data a natural one. Complete data analyses can often be represented in just a few lines of code.”

How are R works in a Nutshell

R works by using a “read-evaluate-print” loop.

  • You type some statements at the command prompt (or statements are read from a file).
  • The parser breaks down syntactically correct statements into machine readable code.
  • The R evaluator executes parsed R expressions and returned values are printed to the console (or some other device) or stored internally as some kind of object.

  • b is the name of a variable: a “container” for the number 2.
  • <- is a the assignment operator.
  • After designating a and b as variables/symbols, the + operator/function accepts the two arguments. The R interpretter recognizes the command as a valid R function, evaluates the function call accordingly and returns/prints the function value to the R console.

Data Structures in R

In most programming languages, variables provide a means of accessing data stored in memory. In R we cannot directly control memory allocation. Rather R comes equipped with a set of data structures which we refer to as objects and which act as containers for our data.

The most basic data structure in R is a vector.

R does not have scalars like other languages.

There are 6 basic (“atomic”) vector types: logical, integer, numeric, complex, character and raw.

Data Structures in R

We can determine the properties of (vector type) objects using the functions:

  • typeof()
  • mode()
  • storage.mode()

We will Focus on Data Frames

  • A dataframe is a special type of list object. A list where all elements have the same length (or row dimension).

  • Could also be viewed as a matrix object that has different “types/modes”…but that is naive.

  • Data frames are used extensively in statistical data analysis.

  • Data franes mimic the strucutres that Excel, SAS, STATA and SPSS users are familiar with (i.e. a flat item by variable matrix of data).

Functions that Act on Data Frames

Data frames typically have certain important attributes:

  • names() give the column names of the data frame
  • row.names() give row/item/case names
  • dim() will tell you the number of rows/columns
  • class() will test that the object is a data frame
  • str() and attributes() tie these info together

Linear Regression

  • Linear regression is an approach for modeling the relationship between a scalar response variable (Y) and one or more predictor variables (X).

\[ y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + \cdots + \beta_p x_{ip} + \varepsilon_i = \mathbf{x}^{\rm T}_i\boldsymbol\beta + \varepsilon_i, \qquad i = 1, \ldots, n, \]

Choose \( \beta \) values to minimize sum of squared errors between observed data and model fit.

\[ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} = \underset{\boldsymbol{\beta}}{\operatorname{arg\,min}}\,S(\boldsymbol{\beta}) \]

Which in the linear model looks like this:

\[ S(\boldsymbol{\beta}) = \sum_{i=1}^{n}\big( y_i - \sum_{j=1}^{p} X_{ij}\beta_j\big)^2 = \bigl\|\mathbf y - \mathbf X \boldsymbol \beta \bigr\|^2. \]

Linear Regression

plot(cars,pch="o",col="orange",cex=2,cex.lab=2)
abline(lm(dist~speed,cars),col="red",lwd=2)
lines(x=cars$speed, y=loess(dist~speed,data=cars)$fitted,col="blue",lwd=2)

Linear Regression (with Matrices)

X <- cbind(rep(1,length(cars$speed)),cars$speed)
y <- cars$dist
beta <- solve(t(X) %*% X) %*% t(X) %*% y
beta

           [,1]
[1,] -17.579095
[2,]   3.932409

Below is the matrix equation we computed in R:

\[ \hat{\boldsymbol\beta} = (\mathbf{X}^{\rm T}\mathbf{X})^{-1} \mathbf{X}^{\rm T}\mathbf{y} = \big(\,{\textstyle\sum} \mathbf{x}_i \mathbf{x}^{\rm T}_i \,\big)^{-1} \big(\,{\textstyle\sum} \mathbf{x}_i y_i \,\big) \]

Linear Regression (Some Assumptions)

  • Correct model specification
  • Weak exogeneity (X's independent of errors)
  • Linearity
  • Homoskedasticity
  • Independent random sample of data
  • Full rank design matrix

Generalized Linear Models

  • Extend linear regression to the case when your response, Y, is not continous (Gaussian)

Case we consider:

  • \( Y \in \{0,1\} \) Logistic regression
  • \( Y \in \{0,1,2,3...\} \) Poisson regression

Alternatively, can think of extending linear model to allow for non-Normal stochastic (error) distribution.

Generalized Linear Models

Three elements of GLM:

  • A probability model for response from exponential family
  • A linear predictor \( \eta=\mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta} \)
  • A link function, \( g() \), such that: \( E(Y)=\mu=g^{-1}(\eta) \)

The model looks as follows:

\[ \operatorname{E}(\mathbf{Y}) = \boldsymbol{\mu} = g^{-1}(\mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}) \]

\[ \operatorname{Var}(\mathbf{Y}) = \operatorname{V}( \boldsymbol{\mu} ) = \operatorname{V}(g^{-1}(\mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta})) \]

More advanced regression models

Generalized estimating equations

  • Extend GLM's to case of non-independent observations
  • Specify working correlation matrix
  • Estimate marginal effects regressors on response

Generalized Linear Mixed Models

  • Extend LM/GLM's to case non-independent observations
  • Include random effects in linear predictor
  • Estimate conditional effect of regressor on response

These models were derived by relaxing some of the assumptions of LM's and GLM's

From GLM's to GEE's

The exponential family of distributions:

\[ f(y; \theta, \phi) = exp \bigg \{ \frac{y\theta - b(\theta)}{a(\phi)} - c(y,\phi) \bigg \} \]

Some theoretical findings:

\[ E(y) = b^{\prime}(\theta) = \mu \]

\[ V(y) = b^{\prime\prime}(\theta)a(\phi) \]

From GLM's to GEE's

The joint density for n independent realizations:

\[ f(y_1...y_n; \theta, \phi) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} exp \bigg \{ \frac{y\theta - b(\theta)}{a(\phi)} - c(y,\phi) \bigg \} \]

And the likelihood looks as follows:

\[ L(\theta, \phi; y_1...y_n) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} exp \bigg \{ \frac{y\theta - b(\theta)}{a(\phi)} - c(y,\phi) \bigg \} \]

And the estimating equation looks as follows:

\[ \frac{\partial{L}}{\partial{\theta}} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{y_i-\mu_i}{a(\phi)} \]

From GLM's to GEE's

Chain rule to get estimating equation in more intuitive form:

\[ \frac{\partial{L}}{\partial{\beta}} = \bigg \{ \frac{\partial{L}}{\partial{\theta}} \frac{\partial{\theta}}{\partial{\mu}} \frac{\partial{\mu}}{\partial{\eta}} \frac{\partial{\eta}}{\partial{\beta_j}} \bigg \} = \bigg \{ \sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{y_i - \mu_i}{a(\phi)}\frac{1}{v(\mu_i)}\frac{\partial{\mu}}{\partial{\eta}}x_{ji} \bigg \} \]

If we choose \( \mu \) and \( v(\mu) \) from single member exponential family than estimating equation estimator agrees with ML.

Otherwise, if we just specify abribtrary function for the mean and variance we get the quasi-likelihood estimating equations:

\[ Q(y;\mu) = \int^\mu \frac{y-\mu^\star}{v(\mu^\star)a(\phi)} \]

From GLM's to GEE's

The estimating equation is sometimes written as:

\[ U(\beta) = \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{\partial \mu_{ij}}{\partial \beta_k} V_i^{-1} \{ Y_i - \mu_i(\beta)\} \]

The parameter estimates solve \( U(\beta)=0 \)

Note in GLM's:

\[ V(\mu_i) = \bigg \{ D(V(\mu_i))^{\frac{1}{2}} I_{n_i*n_i} D(V(\mu_i))^{\frac{1}{2}} \bigg \}_{n_i*n_i} \]

A more relaxed parameterization in GEE's:

\[ V(\mu_i) = \bigg \{ D(V(\mu_i))^{\frac{1}{2}} R(\alpha)_{n_i*n_i} D(V(\mu_i))^{\frac{1}{2}} \bigg \}_{n_i*n_i} \]

GEE Models in R

  • One view: GEE's extend GLM's to case where responses are not i.i.d.

    • Longitudinal data
    • Clustered data
    • etc.

  • Modeling approach is very similar, simply need to extend glm() approach to account for correlated response data (working correlation matrix)

  • Many packages:

    • gee
    • geepack
    • geeM

GEE Models in R

GEE Models in R

  • Estimate marginal effect regressor on response variable

  • Correlation paramters a nuissance, estimated orthogonally to regression parameters

  • GEE's extend on GLM's in R

    • corstr= for working correlation matrix
    • id= for identification cluster variable
    • family= for response distribution
    • link= for link function
    • formula= for linear predictor

  • Generic functions and extractor functions same as GLM/LM

Linear Mixed Models

  • Can be viewed as an extension of linear regression to include random effects in linear predictor.

  • In matrix notation:

\[ \boldsymbol{y} = X \boldsymbol{\beta} + Z \boldsymbol{\gamma} + \boldsymbol{\epsilon} \]

Notation and Assumptions:

  • \( y \) is vector responses, where: \( E(\boldsymbol{y})=X \boldsymbol{\beta} \)
  • \( \boldsymbol{\beta} \) is a vector fixed effects
  • \( \boldsymbol{\gamma} \) is vector random effects
    • \( E(\boldsymbol{\gamma})=0 \) and \( V(\boldsymbol{\gamma})=G \)
  • \( \boldsymbol{\epsilon} \) is vector random effects
    • \( E(\boldsymbol{\epsilon})=0 \) and \( V(\boldsymbol{\epsilon})=R \)

\[ V(\boldsymbol{y}) = V(X \boldsymbol{\beta}) + V(Z \boldsymbol{\gamma}) + V(\boldsymbol{\epsilon}) = ZGZ^T + R \]

Linear Mixed Models

The joint density of \( \boldsymbol{y} \) and \( \boldsymbol{\gamma} \) can be written as:

\[ f(\boldsymbol{y},\boldsymbol{\gamma}) = f(\boldsymbol{y} | \boldsymbol{\gamma}) f(\boldsymbol{\gamma}) \]

If we assume the following:

  • \( \boldsymbol{\gamma} \sim \mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{0},G) \)
  • \( \boldsymbol{\epsilon} \sim \mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{0},R) \)
  • \( Cov(\boldsymbol{\gamma},\boldsymbol{\epsilon})=\boldsymbol{0} \)

We get Henderson's mixed model equations:

\[ \begin{pmatrix} X'R^{-1}X & X'R^{-1}Z \\ Z'R^{-1}X & Z'R^{-1}Z + G^{-1} \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} \\ \hat{\boldsymbol{\gamma}} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} X'R^{-1}\boldsymbol{y} \\ Z'R^{-1}\boldsymbol{y} \end{pmatrix} \]

Estimates of \( \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} \) and \( \hat{\boldsymbol{\gamma}} \) are obtained by application of EM algorithm or other iterative solvers.

Linear Mixed Models in R

Extend the lm() function naturally.

Two main packages:

  • lme4
  • nlme

Main extension is inclusion of random effects in linear predictor (random=) and specification of grouping level variables (id=)

Generalized Linear Mixed Models

2 views of GLMM's:

  • Extend LMM's to non-normal outcomes.
  • Extend GLM's with random effects in the linear predictor.

Many options in R (packages):

  • Frequentist
    • lme4, glmmPQL,glmmADMB
  • Bayesian
    • MCMCglmm, glmmBUGS

And many more

Generalized Linear Mixed Models

Conditional distribution for response given random effects:

\[ f_{y|\gamma}(y|\gamma) = exp \bigg \{ \frac{y\theta - b(\theta)}{a(\phi)} - c(y,\phi) \bigg \} \]

Model transformation mean as linear in fixed/random effects:

\[ E(y|\gamma) = \mu = \ g^{-1}(X \boldsymbol{\beta} + Z \boldsymbol{\gamma}) \]

Which implies:

\[ g(E(y|\gamma)) = g(\mu) = X \boldsymbol{\beta} + Z \boldsymbol{\gamma} \]

A random effect distribution:

\[ \gamma \sim f_{\gamma}(\gamma) \]

Generalized Linear Mixed Models

Marginal properties of response model:

Marginal mean:

\[ E(y) = E(E(y|\gamma)) = E(\mu) = E(g^{-1}(X \boldsymbol{\beta} + Z \boldsymbol{\gamma})) \]

Marginal variance:

\[ V(y) = v(E(y|\gamma)) + E(v(y|\gamma)) \]

Marginal covariance:

\[ cov(y_i,y_j) = cov(E(y_i|\gamma),E(y_j|\gamma)) + E(cov(y_i,y_j|\gamma)) = cov(\mu_i,\mu_j) + E(0) \]

Generalized Linear Mixed Models

Estimation by ML:

\[ f_y(y) = \int f_{y|\gamma}(y|\gamma)f_{\gamma}(\gamma)\partial{\gamma} \]

Log Likelihood:

\[ L = \prod_{i=1}^{n} f_y(y) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} \int f_{y|\gamma}(y|\gamma)f_{\gamma}(\gamma)\partial{\gamma} \]

Hard to maximize because of integral.

  • Gauss-Hermite quadrature
  • Laplacian approximation
  • Penalized quasi-likelihood
  • MCMC (Bayesian) approaches

Overview of Regression in R

In regression analysis we model a response variable as a function of covariates.

Goals:

  • Explanation
  • Prediction

Regression in R

  • Linear models: lm()
  • Generalized linear models: glm()
  • Generalized estimating equations: gee(), geeglm(), geem()
  • Linear mixed models: lmer(), lme()
  • Covariance pattern models: gls()
  • Generalized linear mixed models: glmmPQL(), glmer()

Overview of Regression in R

Some R Ideas:

  • Everything in R is an object

Goal:

  • Create data objects
  • Fit regression models to data
  • Use generic functions to explore model fits
  • Use extractor functions to create new objects
  • Continue exploring

Regression References

  • Brown & Prescott. (2006). Applied Mixed Models in Medicine.
  • McCullagh & Nelder. (1989). Generalized Linear Models.
  • Hardin & Hilbe. (2012). Generalized Estimating Equations.
  • McCulloch, Searle, Neuhaus. (2008). Generalized Linear and Mixed Models.
